1 + x_2 + x_3 = -a \\)\n- \\( x_1x_2 + x_1x_3 + x_2x_3 = b \\)\n- \\( x_1x_2x_3 = -c \\)\n\nSo, the expression we're dealing with is:\n\\[\n\\frac{2a^3 + 27c - 9ab}{\\lambda^3}\n\\]\nLet me see if I can express \\( a, b, c \\) in terms of the roots.\n\nFrom Vieta:\n- \\( a = -(x_1 + x_2 + x_3) \\)\n- \\( b = x_1x_2 + x_1x_3 + x_2x_3 \\)\n- \\( c = -x_1x_2x_3 \\)\n\nSo, substituting these into the numerator:\n\n\\( 2a^3 = 2(- (x1 + x2 + x3))^3 = -2(x1 + x2 + x3)^3 \\)\n\n\\( 27c = 27(-x1x2x3) = -27x1x2x3 \\)\n\n\\( -9ab = -9(- (x1 + x2 + x3))(x1x2 + x1x3 + x2x3) = 9(x1 + x2 + x3)(x1x2 + x1x3 + x2x3) \\)\n\nPutting it all together:\n\\[\n2a^3 + 27c -9ab = -2(x1 + x2 + x3)^3 -27x1x2x3 + 9(x1 + x2 + x3)(x1x2 + x1x3 + x2x3)\n\\]\n\nHmm, that's a bit messy. Maybe there's a way to simplify this expression. Alternatively, maybe we can use substitution to make things easier.\n\nLooking at the transformed polynomial in the reference solution, it's suggested to remove the quadratic term by substituting \\( x = y - \\frac{a}{3} \\). That makes the cubic polynomial in terms of \\( y \\) without the \\( y^2 \\) term. Let me try that.\n\nLet \\( x = y - \\frac{a}{3} \\). Then:\n\n\\( f(x) = (y - a/3)^3 + a(y - a/3)^2 + b(y - a/3) + c \\)\n\nLet me expand this:\n\nFirst, \\( (y - a/3)^3 = y^3 - a y^2 + (a^2/3)y - a^3/27 \\)\n\nThen, \\( a(y - a/3)^2 = a(y^2 - (2a/3)y + a^2/9) = a y^2 - (2a^2/3)y + a^3/9 \\)\n\nAdding these up:\n- \\( y^3 - a y^2 + (a^2/3)y - a^3/27 + a y^2 - (2a^2/3)y + a^3/9 \\)\n\nSimplify:\n- \\( y^3 + [ -a y^2 + a y^2 ] + [ (a^2/3)y - (2a^2/3)y ] + [ -a^3/27 + a^3/9 ] \\)\n\nWhich simplifies to:\n- \\( y^3 - (a^2/3)y + ( -a^3/27 + a^3/9 ) \\)\n\nCalculating constants:\n- \\( -a^3/27 + a^3/9 = (-a^3 + 3a^3)/27 = 2a^3/27 \\)\n\nTherefore, the transformed polynomial is:\n\\[\nF(y) = y^3 - \\left(\\frac{a^2}{3}\\right)y + \\frac{2a^3}{27}\n\\]\nBut wait, in the reference solution, it's written as \\( F(y) = y^3 - (\\frac{a^2}{3} - b)y + \\frac{1}{27}(2a^3 + 27c -9a