ead.\n\nLet me denote:\n\n- \\( \\ln(p) = \\ln(2^{3009}) = 3009 \\cdot \\ln(2) \\)\n\n- \\( \\ln(q) = \\ln(3^{2006}) = 2006 \\cdot \\ln(3) \\)\n\n- \\( \\ln(r) = \\ln(5^{1003}) = 1003 \\cdot \\ln(5) \\)\n\nSo, to compare \\( p, q, r \\), I can compare \\( 3009 \\cdot \\ln(2) \\), \\( 2006 \\cdot \\ln(3) \\), and \\( 1003 \\cdot \\ln(5) \\).\n\nAlternatively, I could also use common logarithms, but natural logarithms might be easier since I remember some approximate values for \\( \\ln(2) \\), \\( \\ln(3) \\), and \\( \\ln(5) \\).\n\nLet me recall the approximate values:\n\n- \\( \\ln(2) \\approx 0.6931 \\)\n\n- \\( \\ln(3) \\approx 1.0986 \\)\n\n- \\( \\ln(5) \\approx 1.6094 \\)\n\nOkay, so plugging these into the expressions:\n\nFirst, compute \\( \\ln(p) = 3009 \\times 0.6931 \\)\n\nThen, \\( \\ln(q) = 2006 \\times 1.0986 \\)\n\nAnd \\( \\ln(r) = 1003 \\times 1.6094 \\)\n\nLet me compute each one step by step.\n\nStarting with \\( \\ln(p) \\):\n\n3009 multiplied by 0.6931.\n\nI can break this down:\n\n3009 * 0.6931\n\nFirst, 3000 * 0.6931 = ?\n\nWell, 3000 * 0.6931 = 3000 * 0.6 + 3000 * 0.0931\n\n= 1800 + 279.3 = 2079.3\n\nThen, 9 * 0.6931 = 6.2379\n\nSo, total \\( \\ln(p) = 2079.3 + 6.2379 = 2085.5379 \\)\n\nSo approximately 2085.54\n\nNext, \\( \\ln(q) = 2006 \\times 1.0986 \\)\n\nAgain, break it down:\n\n2000 * 1.0986 = 2000 * 1 + 2000 * 0.0986 = 2000 + 197.2 = 2197.2\n\nThen, 6 * 1.0986 = 6.5916\n\nSo, total \\( \\ln(q) = 2197.2 + 6.5916 = 2203.7916 \\)\n\nApproximately 2203.79\n\nNow, \\( \\ln(r) = 1003 \\times 1.6094 \\)\n\nLet me compute this as:\n\n1000 * 1.6094 = 1609.4\n\n3 * 1.6094 = 4.8282\n\nSo, total \\( \\ln(r) = 1609.4 + 4.8282 = 1614.2282 \\)\n\nApproximately 1614.23\n\nNow, let me summarize:\n\n- \\( \\ln(p) \\approx 2085.54 \\)\n\n- \\( \\ln(q) \\approx 2203.79 \\)\n\n- \\( \\ln(r) \\approx 1614.23 \\)\n\nSo, ordering these logarithms from smallest to largest:\n\n\\( \\ln(r) < \\ln(p) < \\ln(q) \\)\n\nWhich implies that \\( r < p < q \\)\n\nSo, the order is \\( r < p < q \\), which corresponds to option D.\n\nWait, let me double-check to make sure I didn't make any calculation errors.\n\nCompute \\( \\ln(p) = 3009 * 0.6931 \\). As above, I approximated 3000 * 0.6931 = 2079.3 and 9 * 0.6931 = 6.2379, totaling 2085.5379. That seems right.\n\nFor \\( \\ln(q) = 2006 * 1.0986 \\), I did 2000 * 1.0986 = 2197.2, then 6 * 1.0986 ≈ 6.5916, so total approximately 2203.79. That seems correct.\n\nFor \\( \\ln(r) = 1003 * 1.6094 \\), I did 1000 * 1.6094 = 1609.4, 3 * 1.6094 ≈ 4.8282, totaling 1614.2282. That also looks correct.\n\nSo, yes, ordering by the logarithms:\n\n\\( 1614.23 < 2085.54 < 2203.79 \\)\n\nWhich implies \\( r < p < q \\), which is option D.\n\nAlternatively, to see if maybe I miscalculated, maybe by using base 10 logs.\n\nAlternatively, another approach: taking logarithms with a different base.\n\nBut natural logs seem correct. Let me see:\n\nAnother way is to express all exponents with the same base or exponents. But since the exponents are all different, it's difficult. Alternatively, express each number in terms of exponents that can be compared.\n\nBut probably, using logarithms is the standard approach.\n\nAlternatively, maybe taking log base 2, 3, or 5? Let me try:\n\nBut since we have exponents in different bases, it might complicate.\n\nAlternatively, comparing the exponents:\n\nLet me think about exponents of 2, 3, 5.\n\nWait, maybe I can express each exponent over a common denominator? The exponents are 3009, 2006, and 1003.\n\nLooking at them, 3009 is approximately 1.5 times 2006, and 2006 is approximately 2 times 1003.\n\nSo, 3009 = 3 * 1003, 2006 = 2 * 1003.\n\nWait, 3009 divided by 1003 is 3, yes. Because 1003 * 3 = 3009.\n\nSimilarly, 2006 divided by 1003 is 2, yes.\n\nSo, \\( p = 2^{3009} = (2^3)^{1003} = 8^{1003} \\)\n\n\\( q = 3^{2006} = (3^2)^{1003} = 9^{1003} \\)\n\n\\( r = 5^{1003} \\)\n\nSo now, we have:\n\n\\( p = 8^{1003} \\)\n\n\\( q = 9^{1003} \\)\n\n\\( r = 5^{1003} \\)\n\n