d \\( q \\) are expressed with exponent 1003, just like \\( r \\) already is.\n\nSo now, all three numbers are \\( 5^{1003} \\), \\( 8^{1003} \\), and \\( 9^{1003} \\). Since they all have the same exponent, the order of their sizes is determined solely by their bases. That makes it easier because I just need to compare 5, 8, and 9.\n\nLooking at the bases, 5 is less than 8, which is less than 9. So that should mean \\( 5^{1003} < 8^{1003} < 9^{1003} \\). Therefore, \\( r < p < q \\). \n\nLet me make sure I didn't make a mistake here. Is there a chance that the exponents could reverse the order? But no, because when the exponents are the same, the larger the base, the larger the result. For example, 2^10 is 1024, and 3^10 is 59049, so clearly 3^10 is larger even though 3 is larger than 2.\n\nSo since all exponents are 1003, which is a positive exponent, increasing the base increases the value. Therefore, 5 < 8 < 9 implies \\( r < p < q \\), which corresponds to option D.\n\nWait, just to double-check, let me think about logarithms because sometimes exponents can trick you. Taking the natural logarithm of each number, since logarithm is a monotonically increasing function, it preserves the order. \n\nSo, for \\( p = 8^{1003} \\), the natural log is \\( 1003 \\times \\ln(8) \\). Similarly, \\( q = 9^{1003} \\) becomes \\( 1003 \\times \\ln(9) \\), and \\( r = 5^{1003} \\) becomes \\( 1003 \\times \\ln(5) \\).\n\nSince \\( \\ln(5) \\approx 1.609 \\), \\( \\ln(8) \\approx 2.079 \\), and \\( \\ln(9) \\approx 2.197 \\). Multiplying each by 1003 just scales them but doesn't change their order. So, \\( \\ln(5) < \\ln(8) < \\ln(9) \\), which means \\( r < p < q \\). Yep, that's consistent with my previous conclusion.\n\nI think I'm confident now. The key was to express all three numbers with the same exponent so that the comparison is straightforward by just looking at the bases. Without that step, it might have been harder to see how they compare because of the different exponents. But factoring them into the same exponent makes it much simpler.\n\nSo, in summary, \\( p = 8^{1003} \\), \\( q = 9^{1003} \\), and \\( r = 5^{1003} \\), and since 5 < 8 < 9, it's \\( r < p < q \\). Therefore, the correct answer is D.\n\n**Final Answer**\n\\boxed{D}\n</think>\n\nGiven the values:\n\\[ p = 2^{3009}, \\quad q = 3^{2006}, \\quad r = 5^{1003} \\]\n\n1. Express \\( p \\) and \\( q \\) in terms of powers of the same base:\n   \\[ p = 2^{3009} = (2^3)^{1003} = 8^{1003} \\]\n   \\[ q = 3^{2006} = (3^2)^{1003} = 9^{1003} \\]\n   Note: \\( r = 5^{1003} \\) is already expressed as a power.\n\n2. Compare the magnitudes:\n   To compare \\( p, q, \\) and \\( r \\), we now look at the factors 8, 9, and 5 which are:\n   \\[ 8^{1003}, \\quad 9^{1003}, \\quad \\text{and} \\quad 5^{1003} \\]\n\n3. Analyze the base values:\n   - Base 8: \\( 8 = 2^3 \\)\n   - Base 9: \\( 9 = 3^2 \\)\n   - Base 5: \\( 5 \\)\n\n4. Since the common exponent in all terms is \\( 1003 \\), we compare the bases:\n   - Clearly, \\( 5 < 8 < 9 \\)\n\n5. Therefore, since all exponents are equal, the order of the original terms follows the order of their bases:\n   \\[ 5^{1003} < 8^{1003} < 9^{1003} \\]\n   \\[ r < p < q \\]\n\nThus, the true statement is \\( r < p < q \\).\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{D}\n\\]"}
