f triples without any even numbers**: Even numbers in 1-6 are 2, 4, 6. So, if all numbers are odd, they can be 1, 3, or 5. That's 3 choices per position. Hence, the number of such triples is \\(3^3 = 27\\).\n\n4. **Number of triples without any 5s and without any even numbers**: These are triples where all numbers are odd and not 5, so they can only be 1 or 3. That gives 2 choices per position, leading to \\(2^3 = 8\\) such triples.\n\nNow, using the principle of inclusion-exclusion, the number of triples that have at least one 5 and at least one even number is equal to the total number of triples minus the number without any 5s minus the number without any evens plus the number without both 5s and evens. So, that would be:\n\n\\[ 216 - 125 - 27 + 8 = 72 \\]\n\nLet me verify this with another method to ensure accuracy.\n\n**Alternative approach: Counting directly**\n\nWe can break it down into cases based on the number of 5s:\n\n- **Case 1: Exactly one 5**. Choose which position is 5 (3 choices). The remaining two positions must have at least one even number. The number of ways to have at least one even in two positions is total ways minus all odds. Each of the remaining two positions can be 1, 3, 5 (but since we already have one 5, they can't be 5 again for this case). Wait, actually, in this case, the remaining two positions can be 1, 2, 3, 4, 6. We need at least one of them to be even. So, the number of such pairs is \\(5 \\times 5 - 3 \\times 3 = 25 - 9 = 16\\). Wait, hold on, that might not be right.\n\nActually, for each of the remaining two positions, there are 5 choices (1-6 excluding 5). Out of these, 2 are even (2,4,6) and 3 are odd (1,3). So, the number of pairs with at least one even is total pairs minus all odd pairs. Total pairs: \\(5 \\times 5 = 25\\). All odd pairs: \\(3 \\times 3 = 9\\). Therefore, the number of pairs with at least one even is \\(25 - 9 = 16\\). So, for this case, the number of triples is \\(3 \\times 16 = 48\\).\n\n- **Case 2: Exactly two 5s**. Choose the two positions for 5s: \\(\\binom{3}{2} = 3\\). The remaining position must be an even number (since we need at least one even). There are 3 choices for the even number. So, the number of triples is \\(3 \\times 3 = 9\\).\n\n- **Case 3: Exactly three 5s**. This case would have all numbers as 5, which are odd, so no evens. Hence, this case contributes 0.\n\nAdding up the contributions from each case: \\(48 + 9 + 0 = 57\\). Wait, that's different from 72. Hmm, I must have made a mistake here.\n\nWait a second, in case 1, I think I miscounted. When exactly one 5 is present, the remaining two numbers can be anything except 5, but need to have at least one even. However, in the remaining two positions, can they include 5? No, because we're in the case where exactly one 5 is present. So, each of the remaining two positions can be 1,2,3,4,6. Wait, so in each of these positions, 2 are even (2,4,6) and 3 are odd (1,3). So, the number of ways to have at least one even in the remaining two positions is \\(5 \\times 5 - 3 \\times 3 = 25 - 9 = 16\\). But 5 choices per position for the remaining two numbers, so 25 total, minus 9 all odds, giving 16. So, 3 positions to place the 5, each with 16 possibilities, leading to 3*16=48.\n\nCase 2: exactly two 5s. The remaining number must be even, so 3 choices. So 3*3=9.\n\nCase 3: 0.\n\nTotal: 48 + 9 = 57.\n\nWait, but that contradicts the inclusion-exclusion result of 72. Where did I go wrong?\n\nOh! Wait, in the inclusion-exclusion, we found that 72 triples have at least one 5 and at least one even, but in this case approach, we get 57. There's a discrepancy here.\n\nWait, maybe the error is in the case approach. Let me think again.\n\nIn case 1: exactly one 5. The remaining two numbers must have at least one even. So, we have 5 choices for each of the remaining two positions, but not 5. Wait, no: we already have one 5, so the remaining two numbers can't be 5. So each position has 5 choices: 1,2,3,4,6. Out of these, 2 are even and 3 are odd. So, the number of ways to have at least one even is 5*5 - 3*3 = 16, as before. So 3*16=48.\n\nCase 2: exactly two 5s. The remaining position must be even. There are 3 choices for the even number. So, 3*3=9.\n\nCase 3: three 5s. 0.\n\nSo total is 48 + 9 = 57.\n\nBut inclusion-exclusion gave 72. So which one is correct?\n\nWait, perhaps my inclusion-exclusion is wrong.\n\nWait, total triples: 216.\n\nNumber of triples without any 5s: 125.\n\nNumber of triples without any evens: 27.\n\nNumber of triples without any 5s and without any evens: 8.\n\nTherefore, |A ∩ B| = 216 - 125 -27 +8=72.\n\nBut in the case approach, we only have 57.\n\nWait, this discrepancy suggests an error in one of the approaches.\n\nWait, perhaps in the case approach, we are not considering that when exactly one 5 is present, the remaining two positions could still have 5s. But wait, no, because in case 1, exactly one 5. So the other two can't be 5.\n\nWait, so the case approach seems accurate, but why does inclusion-exclusion give a different answer?\n\nWait, maybe my inclusion-exclusion is wrong. Let me double-check.\n\nWait, inclusion-exclusion formula: |A ∩ B| = |A| + |B| - |A ∪ B|. Wait, no, that's not correct. The formula I used was:\n\n|A ∩ B| = Total - |not A ∪ not B| = Total - |not A| - |not B| + |not A ∩ not B|. \n\nWait, that is correct. So:\n\nTotal: 216.\n\n|not A|: 125.\n\n|not B|: 27.\n\n|not A ∩ not B|:8.\n\nSo 216 -125 -27 +8=72.\n\nBut in the case approach, we have only 57. So, perhaps the case approach is undercounting.\n\nWait, maybe I made a mistake in the case approach. Let me think again.\n\nIn case 1: exactly one 5. The remaining two numbers"}
